{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SUwWuVkUxkL5CaShWDyjbk","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"2026 ordinary income tax brackets IRS filing status\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"2026 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation\",\"url\":\"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/\"},{\"title\":\"Federal income tax rates and brackets | Internal Revenue Service\",\"url\":\"https://www.irs.gov/filing/federal-income-tax-rates-and-brackets\"},{\"title\":\"IRS releases tax inflation adjustments for tax year 2026, including amendments from the One, Big, Beautiful Bill | Internal Revenue Service\",\"url\":\"https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill\"},{\"title\":\"The Updated Federal Income Tax Brackets for the 2026 Tax Year | Chase\",\"url\":\"https://www.chase.com/personal/investments/learning-and-insights/article/tax-brackets-2026\"},{\"title\":\"2025-2026 Federal Tax Brackets and Income Rates - NerdWallet\",\"url\":\"https://www.nerdwallet.com/taxes/learn/federal-income-tax-brackets\"},{\"title\":\"IRS Releases 2026 Income Tax Brackets\",\"url\":\"https://www.aarp.org/money/taxes/income-tax-brackets-2026/\"},{\"title\":\"IRS Releases 2026 Tax Brackets, Contribution Limits, Other Tax Updates | PERA On The Issues\",\"url\":\"https://copera.org/pera-on-the-issues/irs-releases-2026-tax-brackets-contribution-limits-other-tax-updates\"},{\"title\":\"The IRS released new tax brackets for 2026. Some Americans will save thousands while others won't be so lucky\",\"url\":\"https://finance.yahoo.com/news/irs-released-tax-brackets-2026-121500860.html\"},{\"title\":\"Income Tax Brackets and Rates for 2025, 2026, and 2027\",\"url\":\"https://www.efile.com/tax-brackets-2025-2026-2027/\"},{\"title\":\"2026 individual tax brackets, and tips for understanding what you pay | Principal\",\"url\":\"https://www.principal.com/individuals/learn/individual-tax-brackets-understand-what-you-pay\"}]\n\nHere are the **2026 federal ordinary income tax brackets** based on IRS guidance:\n\n## Overview\n\nThe federal income tax has seven tax rates in 2026: 10 percent, 12 percent, 22 percent, 24 percent, 32 percent, 35 percent, and 37 percent. The tax year 2026 adjustments generally apply to tax returns filed in 2027.\n\n---\n\n## 2026 Tax Brackets by Filing Status\n\n### Single Filers\n\n| Tax Rate | Taxable Income |\n|----------|----------------|\n| 10% | $0 – $12,400 |\n| 12% | $12,401 – $50,400 |\n| 22% | $50,401 – $105,700 |\n| 24% | $105,701 – $201,775 |\n| 32% | $201,776 – $256,225 |\n| 35% | $256,226 – $640,600 |\n| 37% | Over $640,600 |\n\n\n### Married Filing Jointly\n\n| Tax Rate | Taxable Income |\n|----------|----------------|\n| 10% | $0 – $24,800 |\n| 12% | $24,801 – $100,800 |\n| 22% | $100,801 – $211,400 |\n| 24% | $211,401 – $403,550 |\n| 32% | $403,551 – $512,450 |\n| 35% | $512,451 – $768,700 |\n| 37% | Over $768,700 |\n\n\n---\n\n## Key Highlights\n\n- **Top rate:** For tax year 2026, the top tax rate remains 37% for individual single taxpayers with incomes greater than $640,600 ($768,700 for married couples filing jointly).\n- **Lowest bracket expansion:** The upper end of the lowest tax bracket (10%) has been raised from $11,925 in 2025 to $12,400 in 2026.\n\n## Standard Deduction for 2026\n\n- For tax year 2026, the standard deduction increases to $32,200 for married couples filing jointly. For single taxpayers and married individuals filing separately, the standard deduction rises to $16,100, and for heads of households, the standard deduction will be $24,150.\n\n## Inflation Adjustments\n\nThe OBBBA (One Big Beautiful Bill Act) made permanent the TCJA ordinary income tax structure and made an additional inflation adjustment for income subject to the bottom two brackets (10 percent and 12 percent), providing a 4 percent inflation adjustment for the bottom two brackets and a 2.3 percent increase for the higher brackets.\n\n## Source\n\nThese figures come from the Internal Revenue Service's \"Revenue Procedure 2025-32.\" You can view the official IRS page at [irs.gov](https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill) for full details on all filing statuses.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"a33aee7a-545e-4103-84a2-5046b7c52b4e","tool_use_result":{"query":"2026 ordinary income tax brackets IRS filing status","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01UT9WSwyt8JLrpg9dBvbmZB","content":[{"title":"2026 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation","url":"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/"},{"title":"Federal income tax rates and brackets | Internal Revenue Service","url":"https://www.irs.gov/filing/federal-income-tax-rates-and-brackets"},{"title":"IRS releases tax inflation adjustments for tax year 2026, including amendments from the One, Big, Beautiful Bill | Internal Revenue Service","url":"https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill"},{"title":"The Updated Federal Income Tax Brackets for the 2026 Tax Year | Chase","url":"https://www.chase.com/personal/investments/learning-and-insights/article/tax-brackets-2026"},{"title":"2025-2026 Federal Tax Brackets and Income Rates - NerdWallet","url":"https://www.nerdwallet.com/taxes/learn/federal-income-tax-brackets"},{"title":"IRS Releases 2026 Income Tax Brackets","url":"https://www.aarp.org/money/taxes/income-tax-brackets-2026/"},{"title":"IRS Releases 2026 Tax Brackets, Contribution Limits, Other Tax Updates | PERA On The Issues","url":"https://copera.org/pera-on-the-issues/irs-releases-2026-tax-brackets-contribution-limits-other-tax-updates"},{"title":"The IRS released new tax brackets for 2026. Some Americans will save thousands while others won't be so lucky","url":"https://finance.yahoo.com/news/irs-released-tax-brackets-2026-121500860.html"},{"title":"Income Tax Brackets and Rates for 2025, 2026, and 2027","url":"https://www.efile.com/tax-brackets-2025-2026-2027/"},{"title":"2026 individual tax brackets, and tips for understanding what you pay | Principal","url":"https://www.principal.com/individuals/learn/individual-tax-brackets-understand-what-you-pay"}]},"Here are the **2026 federal ordinary income tax brackets** based on IRS guidance:\n\n## Overview\n\nThe federal income tax has seven tax rates in 2026: 10 percent, 12 percent, 22 percent, 24 percent, 32 percent, 35 percent, and 37 percent. The tax year 2026 adjustments generally apply to tax returns filed in 2027.\n\n---\n\n## 2026 Tax Brackets by Filing Status\n\n### Single Filers\n\n| Tax Rate | Taxable Income |\n|----------|----------------|\n| 10% | $0 – $12,400 |\n| 12% | $12,401 – $50,400 |\n| 22% | $50,401 – $105,700 |\n| 24% | $105,701 – $201,775 |\n| 32% | $201,776 – $256,225 |\n| 35% | $256,226 – $640,600 |\n| 37% | Over $640,600 |\n\n\n### Married Filing Jointly\n\n| Tax Rate | Taxable Income |\n|----------|----------------|\n| 10% | $0 – $24,800 |\n| 12% | $24,801 – $100,800 |\n| 22% | $100,801 – $211,400 |\n| 24% | $211,401 – $403,550 |\n| 32% | $403,551 – $512,450 |\n| 35% | $512,451 – $768,700 |\n| 37% | Over $768,700 |\n\n\n---\n\n## Key Highlights\n\n- **Top rate:** For tax year 2026, the top tax rate remains 37% for individual single taxpayers with incomes greater than $640,600 ($768,700 for married couples filing jointly).\n- **Lowest bracket expansion:** The upper end of the lowest tax bracket (10%) has been raised from $11,925 in 2025 to $12,400 in 2026.\n\n## Standard Deduction for 2026\n\n- For tax year 2026, the standard deduction increases to $32,200 for married couples filing jointly. For single taxpayers and married individuals filing separately, the standard deduction rises to $16,100, and for heads of households, the standard deduction will be $24,150.\n\n## Inflation Adjustments\n\nThe OBBBA (One Big Beautiful Bill Act) made permanent the TCJA ordinary income tax structure and made an additional inflation adjustment for income subject to the bottom two brackets (10 percent and 12 percent), providing a 4 percent inflation adjustment for the bottom two brackets and a 2.3 percent increase for the higher brackets.\n\n## Source\n\nThese figures come from the Internal Revenue Service's \"Revenue Procedure 2025-32.\" You can view the official IRS page at [irs.gov](https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill) for full details on all filing statuses."],"durationSeconds":22.918931166}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Rmzc6VMa45efWDLELyfo2s","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Revenue Procedure 2025-32 2026 federal income tax brackets IRS\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"2026 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation\",\"url\":\"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/\"},{\"title\":\"IRS releases tax inflation adjustments for tax year 2026, including amendments from the One, Big, Beautiful Bill | Internal Revenue Service\",\"url\":\"https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill\"},{\"title\":\"Federal income tax rates and brackets | Internal Revenue Service\",\"url\":\"https://www.irs.gov/filing/federal-income-tax-rates-and-brackets\"},{\"title\":\"26 CFR 601.602: Tax forms and instructions.\",\"url\":\"https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-25-32.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"2026 quick tax reference guide 2026 federal income tax brackets1 TAXABLE INCOME\",\"url\":\"https://www.tiaa.org/public/pdf/q/quick_tax_reference_guide.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"2025 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation\",\"url\":\"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2025-tax-brackets/\"},{\"title\":\"2025 and 2026 tax brackets and federal income tax rates | Fidelity\",\"url\":\"https://www.fidelity.com/learning-center/personal-finance/tax-brackets\"},{\"title\":\"2025-2026 Tax Brackets and Tax Rates - TurboTax Tax Tips & Videos\",\"url\":\"https://turbotax.intuit.com/tax-tips/irs-tax-return/current-federal-tax-rate-schedules/L7Bjs1EAD\"},{\"title\":\"2025 Federal Income Tax Brackets and Other 2025 Tax Rules\",\"url\":\"https://bipartisanpolicy.org/explainer/2025-federal-income-tax-brackets-and-other-2025-tax-rules/\"},{\"title\":\"IRS Inflation Adjustments for Tax Year 2026\",\"url\":\"https://blog.webce.com/article/irs-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026\"}]\n\nHere's a summary of the key information from **Revenue Procedure 2025-32** regarding the **2026 federal income tax brackets**:\n\n## Overview\n\nThe Internal Revenue Service announced the tax year 2026 annual inflation adjustments for more than 60 tax provisions, including the tax rate schedules and other tax changes. Revenue Procedure 2025-32 provides details about these annual adjustments, which generally apply to tax returns filed in 2027.\n\nFor tax year 2026, the IRS issues its annual adjustments through Revenue Procedure 2025-32, incorporating changes enacted by the One Big Beautiful Bill Act (OBBBA).\n\n## 2026 Tax Rates\n\nThe federal income tax has seven tax rates in 2026: 10 percent, 12 percent, 22 percent, 24 percent, 32 percent, 35 percent, and 37 percent.\n\nSection 70101 of the OBBBA amends § 1(j) to make the tax rate tables that were effective for taxable years beginning after December 31, 2017, and before January 1, 2026, permanent.\n\n## 2026 Tax Brackets (Income Thresholds)\n\nThe brackets for 2026 are as follows:\n- **37%** for incomes above $640,600 (single) or $768,700 (married filing jointly)\n- **35%** for incomes above $256,225 (single) or $512,450 (married filing jointly)\n- **32%** for incomes above $201,775 (single) or $403,550 (married filing jointly)\n- **24%** for incomes above $105,700 (single) or $211,400 (married filing jointly)\n- **22%** for incomes above $50,400 (single) or $100,800 (married filing jointly)\n- **12%** for incomes above $12,400 (single) or $24,800 (married filing jointly)\n- **10%** for incomes at or below $12,400 (single) or $24,800 (married filing jointly)\n\n## Standard Deduction for 2026\n\nFor tax year 2026, the standard deduction increases to $32,200 for married couples filing jointly. For single taxpayers and married individuals filing separately, the standard deduction rises to $16,100 for tax year 2026, and for heads of households, the standard deduction will be $24,150.\n\nSeniors over age 65 may claim an additional standard deduction of $2,050 for single filers and $1,650 for joint filers.\n\n## Other Notable Adjustments\n\n- **Earned Income Tax Credit:** The tax year 2026 maximum EITC amount is $8,231 for qualifying taxpayers who have three or more qualifying children, up from $8,046 for tax year 2025.\n- **Foreign Earned Income Exclusion:** For tax year 2026, the foreign earned income exclusion is $132,900, up from $130,000 for tax year 2025.\n- **Gift Tax Exclusion:** In 2026, the first $19,000 of gifts to any person is excluded from tax, remaining the same as in 2025.\n- **AMT Exemption:** The AMT exemption amount for 2026 is $90,100 for singles and $140,200 for married couples filing jointly.\n- **Health FSA:** For tax years beginning in 2026, the dollar limitation for voluntary employee salary reductions for contributions to health flexible spending arrangements increases to $3,400, up $100 from the prior year.\n- **Personal Exemptions:** For tax year 2026, personal exemptions remain at 0, as in tax year 2025. The elimination of the personal exemption was a provision in the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 and was made permanent by OBBB.\n\nOn average, tax parameters that are adjusted for inflation will increase by about 2.7 percent.\n\nYou can view the full text of Revenue Procedure 2025-32 directly on the [IRS website (PDF)](https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-25-32.pdf).\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"ba3a34ac-a8b4-42a3-abbf-d44e4b89ba7f","tool_use_result":{"query":"Revenue Procedure 2025-32 2026 federal income tax brackets IRS","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01H2xWrHFTvfi2esSGsfqe6F","content":[{"title":"2026 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation","url":"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/"},{"title":"IRS releases tax inflation adjustments for tax year 2026, including amendments from the One, Big, Beautiful Bill | Internal Revenue Service","url":"https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill"},{"title":"Federal income tax rates and brackets | Internal Revenue Service","url":"https://www.irs.gov/filing/federal-income-tax-rates-and-brackets"},{"title":"26 CFR 601.602: Tax forms and instructions.","url":"https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-25-32.pdf"},{"title":"2026 quick tax reference guide 2026 federal income tax brackets1 TAXABLE INCOME","url":"https://www.tiaa.org/public/pdf/q/quick_tax_reference_guide.pdf"},{"title":"2025 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation","url":"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2025-tax-brackets/"},{"title":"2025 and 2026 tax brackets and federal income tax rates | Fidelity","url":"https://www.fidelity.com/learning-center/personal-finance/tax-brackets"},{"title":"2025-2026 Tax Brackets and Tax Rates - TurboTax Tax Tips & Videos","url":"https://turbotax.intuit.com/tax-tips/irs-tax-return/current-federal-tax-rate-schedules/L7Bjs1EAD"},{"title":"2025 Federal Income Tax Brackets and Other 2025 Tax Rules","url":"https://bipartisanpolicy.org/explainer/2025-federal-income-tax-brackets-and-other-2025-tax-rules/"},{"title":"IRS Inflation Adjustments for Tax Year 2026","url":"https://blog.webce.com/article/irs-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026"}]},"Here's a summary of the key information from **Revenue Procedure 2025-32** regarding the **2026 federal income tax brackets**:\n\n## Overview\n\nThe Internal Revenue Service announced the tax year 2026 annual inflation adjustments for more than 60 tax provisions, including the tax rate schedules and other tax changes. Revenue Procedure 2025-32 provides details about these annual adjustments, which generally apply to tax returns filed in 2027.\n\nFor tax year 2026, the IRS issues its annual adjustments through Revenue Procedure 2025-32, incorporating changes enacted by the One Big Beautiful Bill Act (OBBBA).\n\n## 2026 Tax Rates\n\nThe federal income tax has seven tax rates in 2026: 10 percent, 12 percent, 22 percent, 24 percent, 32 percent, 35 percent, and 37 percent.\n\nSection 70101 of the OBBBA amends § 1(j) to make the tax rate tables that were effective for taxable years beginning after December 31, 2017, and before January 1, 2026, permanent.\n\n## 2026 Tax Brackets (Income Thresholds)\n\nThe brackets for 2026 are as follows:\n- **37%** for incomes above $640,600 (single) or $768,700 (married filing jointly)\n- **35%** for incomes above $256,225 (single) or $512,450 (married filing jointly)\n- **32%** for incomes above $201,775 (single) or $403,550 (married filing jointly)\n- **24%** for incomes above $105,700 (single) or $211,400 (married filing jointly)\n- **22%** for incomes above $50,400 (single) or $100,800 (married filing jointly)\n- **12%** for incomes above $12,400 (single) or $24,800 (married filing jointly)\n- **10%** for incomes at or below $12,400 (single) or $24,800 (married filing jointly)\n\n## Standard Deduction for 2026\n\nFor tax year 2026, the standard deduction increases to $32,200 for married couples filing jointly. For single taxpayers and married individuals filing separately, the standard deduction rises to $16,100 for tax year 2026, and for heads of households, the standard deduction will be $24,150.\n\nSeniors over age 65 may claim an additional standard deduction of $2,050 for single filers and $1,650 for joint filers.\n\n## Other Notable Adjustments\n\n- **Earned Income Tax Credit:** The tax year 2026 maximum EITC amount is $8,231 for qualifying taxpayers who have three or more qualifying children, up from $8,046 for tax year 2025.\n- **Foreign Earned Income Exclusion:** For tax year 2026, the foreign earned income exclusion is $132,900, up from $130,000 for tax year 2025.\n- **Gift Tax Exclusion:** In 2026, the first $19,000 of gifts to any person is excluded from tax, remaining the same as in 2025.\n- **AMT Exemption:** The AMT exemption amount for 2026 is $90,100 for singles and $140,200 for married couples filing jointly.\n- **Health FSA:** For tax years beginning in 2026, the dollar limitation for voluntary employee salary reductions for contributions to health flexible spending arrangements increases to $3,400, up $100 from the prior year.\n- **Personal Exemptions:** For tax year 2026, personal exemptions remain at 0, as in tax year 2025. The elimination of the personal exemption was a provision in the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 and was made permanent by OBBB.\n\nOn average, tax parameters that are adjusted for inflation will increase by about 2.7 percent.\n\nYou can view the full text of Revenue Procedure 2025-32 directly on the [IRS website (PDF)](https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-25-32.pdf)."],"durationSeconds":27.695685708}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NbT9rfHjnbHgwbjKMYgpbu","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"2026 federal income tax rate tables IRS revenue procedure 2025-32\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"2026 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation\",\"url\":\"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/\"},{\"title\":\"IRS releases tax inflation adjustments for tax year 2026, including amendments from the One, Big, Beautiful Bill | Internal Revenue Service\",\"url\":\"https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill\"},{\"title\":\"Federal income tax rates and brackets | Internal Revenue Service\",\"url\":\"https://www.irs.gov/filing/federal-income-tax-rates-and-brackets\"},{\"title\":\"26 CFR 601.602: Tax forms and instructions.\",\"url\":\"https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-25-32.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Internal Revenue Bulletin: 2025-32 | Internal Revenue Service\",\"url\":\"https://www.irs.gov/irb/2025-32_IRB\"},{\"title\":\"2026 Inflation Adjustments for Tax Professionals: Revenue Procedure 2025-32 Analysis — Current Federal Tax Developments\",\"url\":\"https://www.currentfederaltaxdevelopments.com/blog/2025/10/9/2026-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-professionals-revenue-procedure-2025-32-analysis\"},{\"title\":\"2025 and 2026 tax brackets and federal income tax rates | Fidelity\",\"url\":\"https://www.fidelity.com/learning-center/personal-finance/tax-brackets\"},{\"title\":\"2025-2026 Tax Brackets and Tax Rates - TurboTax Tax Tips & Videos\",\"url\":\"https://turbotax.intuit.com/tax-tips/irs-tax-return/current-federal-tax-rate-schedules/L7Bjs1EAD\"},{\"title\":\"2025-2026 Tax Brackets & Federal Income Tax Rates | H&R Block®\",\"url\":\"https://www.hrblock.com/tax-center/irs/tax-brackets-and-rates/what-are-the-tax-brackets/\"},{\"title\":\"2025 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation\",\"url\":\"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2025-tax-brackets/\"}]\n\nHere's a summary of the key findings from **IRS Revenue Procedure 2025-32** regarding **2026 federal income tax rates and brackets**:\n\n## Overview\n\nThe IRS has issued Revenue Procedure 2025-32, which modifies prior guidance (Rev. Proc. 2024-40) to incorporate statutory changes made by Public Law 119-21, commonly known as the One, Big, Beautiful Bill Act (OBBBA). The new inflation adjustments are for tax year 2026, for which taxpayers will file tax returns in early 2027.\n\n## 2026 Tax Rates\n\nThe federal income tax has seven tax rates in 2026: 10 percent, 12 percent, 22 percent, 24 percent, 32 percent, 35 percent, and 37 percent.\n\nSection 70101 of the OBBBA amends § 1(j) to make the tax rate tables that were effective for taxable years beginning after December 31, 2017, and before January 1, 2026, permanent.\n\nOn average, tax parameters that are adjusted for inflation will increase by about 2.7 percent.\n\n## 2026 Standard Deduction\n\nFor tax year 2026, the standard deduction increases to $32,200 for married couples filing jointly. For single taxpayers and married individuals filing separately, the standard deduction rises to $16,100 for tax year 2026, and for heads of households, the standard deduction will be $24,150.\n\nThe standard deduction will increase by $350 for single filers and by $700 for joint filers compared to the 2025 tax year.\n\n### Additional Standard Deduction for Seniors/Blind\nThe additional standard deduction amount for the aged or the blind is $1,650. If the individual is also unmarried and not a surviving spouse, this additional amount increases to $2,050.\n\n### New Senior Deduction (OBBBA)\nOn top of this, taxpayers aged 65 and older both itemizing and claiming the standard deduction may claim a new $6,000 deduction per qualifying taxpayer, phasing out at a six percent rate for those earning over $75,000 (single) and $150,000 (joint) as part of the separate senior deduction under the OBBBA.\n\n## Other Key 2026 Adjustments\n\n- **Personal Exemptions:** For tax year 2026, personal exemptions remain at $0. The elimination of the personal exemption was a provision in the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 and was made permanent by OBBB.\n\n- **Earned Income Tax Credit:** The tax year 2026 maximum EITC amount is $8,231 for qualifying taxpayers who have three or more qualifying children, up from $8,046 for tax year 2025.\n\n- **Gift Tax Exclusion:** For tax year 2026, the annual exclusion for gifts remains at $19,000. However, the annual exclusion for gifts to a spouse who is not a citizen of the United States increases to $194,000 for calendar year 2026, up $4,000 from calendar year 2025.\n\n- **Foreign Earned Income Exclusion:** For tax year 2026, the foreign earned income exclusion is $132,900, up from $130,000 for tax year 2025.\n\n- **Transportation Fringe Benefit:** For tax year 2026, the monthly limitation for the qualified transportation fringe benefit and the monthly limitation for qualified parking increases to $340, up $15 from 2025.\n\n- **Health FSA:** For tax years beginning in 2026, the dollar limitation for voluntary employee salary reductions for contributions to health flexible spending arrangements increases to $3,400, up $100 from the prior year.\n\n- **AMT Exemption:** The AMT exemption amount for 2026 is $90,100 for singles and $140,200 for married couples filing jointly.\n\n- **Estate Tax Exemption:** The OBBBA made the TCJA-era estate tax exemption permanent and raised it to $15 million per person beginning in 2026, adjusted for inflation moving forward.\n\n## Source Documents\n\n- The full text of Revenue Procedure 2025-32 is available directly from the IRS at: [irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-25-32.pdf](https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-25-32.pdf)\n- The IRS news release is at: [irs.gov newsroom](https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill)\n- The Tax Foundation's analysis is at: [taxfoundation.org](https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/)\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"d757279b-34af-4347-a461-09e9aa837aff","tool_use_result":{"query":"2026 federal income tax rate tables IRS revenue procedure 2025-32","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_0122PCcVyRvEkBRHAks8v9vU","content":[{"title":"2026 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation","url":"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/"},{"title":"IRS releases tax inflation adjustments for tax year 2026, including amendments from the One, Big, Beautiful Bill | Internal Revenue Service","url":"https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill"},{"title":"Federal income tax rates and brackets | Internal Revenue Service","url":"https://www.irs.gov/filing/federal-income-tax-rates-and-brackets"},{"title":"26 CFR 601.602: Tax forms and instructions.","url":"https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-25-32.pdf"},{"title":"Internal Revenue Bulletin: 2025-32 | Internal Revenue Service","url":"https://www.irs.gov/irb/2025-32_IRB"},{"title":"2026 Inflation Adjustments for Tax Professionals: Revenue Procedure 2025-32 Analysis — Current Federal Tax Developments","url":"https://www.currentfederaltaxdevelopments.com/blog/2025/10/9/2026-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-professionals-revenue-procedure-2025-32-analysis"},{"title":"2025 and 2026 tax brackets and federal income tax rates | Fidelity","url":"https://www.fidelity.com/learning-center/personal-finance/tax-brackets"},{"title":"2025-2026 Tax Brackets and Tax Rates - TurboTax Tax Tips & Videos","url":"https://turbotax.intuit.com/tax-tips/irs-tax-return/current-federal-tax-rate-schedules/L7Bjs1EAD"},{"title":"2025-2026 Tax Brackets & Federal Income Tax Rates | H&R Block®","url":"https://www.hrblock.com/tax-center/irs/tax-brackets-and-rates/what-are-the-tax-brackets/"},{"title":"2025 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation","url":"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2025-tax-brackets/"}]},"Here's a summary of the key findings from **IRS Revenue Procedure 2025-32** regarding **2026 federal income tax rates and brackets**:\n\n## Overview\n\nThe IRS has issued Revenue Procedure 2025-32, which modifies prior guidance (Rev. Proc. 2024-40) to incorporate statutory changes made by Public Law 119-21, commonly known as the One, Big, Beautiful Bill Act (OBBBA). The new inflation adjustments are for tax year 2026, for which taxpayers will file tax returns in early 2027.\n\n## 2026 Tax Rates\n\nThe federal income tax has seven tax rates in 2026: 10 percent, 12 percent, 22 percent, 24 percent, 32 percent, 35 percent, and 37 percent.\n\nSection 70101 of the OBBBA amends § 1(j) to make the tax rate tables that were effective for taxable years beginning after December 31, 2017, and before January 1, 2026, permanent.\n\nOn average, tax parameters that are adjusted for inflation will increase by about 2.7 percent.\n\n## 2026 Standard Deduction\n\nFor tax year 2026, the standard deduction increases to $32,200 for married couples filing jointly. For single taxpayers and married individuals filing separately, the standard deduction rises to $16,100 for tax year 2026, and for heads of households, the standard deduction will be $24,150.\n\nThe standard deduction will increase by $350 for single filers and by $700 for joint filers compared to the 2025 tax year.\n\n### Additional Standard Deduction for Seniors/Blind\nThe additional standard deduction amount for the aged or the blind is $1,650. If the individual is also unmarried and not a surviving spouse, this additional amount increases to $2,050.\n\n### New Senior Deduction (OBBBA)\nOn top of this, taxpayers aged 65 and older both itemizing and claiming the standard deduction may claim a new $6,000 deduction per qualifying taxpayer, phasing out at a six percent rate for those earning over $75,000 (single) and $150,000 (joint) as part of the separate senior deduction under the OBBBA.\n\n## Other Key 2026 Adjustments\n\n- **Personal Exemptions:** For tax year 2026, personal exemptions remain at $0. The elimination of the personal exemption was a provision in the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 and was made permanent by OBBB.\n\n- **Earned Income Tax Credit:** The tax year 2026 maximum EITC amount is $8,231 for qualifying taxpayers who have three or more qualifying children, up from $8,046 for tax year 2025.\n\n- **Gift Tax Exclusion:** For tax year 2026, the annual exclusion for gifts remains at $19,000. However, the annual exclusion for gifts to a spouse who is not a citizen of the United States increases to $194,000 for calendar year 2026, up $4,000 from calendar year 2025.\n\n- **Foreign Earned Income Exclusion:** For tax year 2026, the foreign earned income exclusion is $132,900, up from $130,000 for tax year 2025.\n\n- **Transportation Fringe Benefit:** For tax year 2026, the monthly limitation for the qualified transportation fringe benefit and the monthly limitation for qualified parking increases to $340, up $15 from 2025.\n\n- **Health FSA:** For tax years beginning in 2026, the dollar limitation for voluntary employee salary reductions for contributions to health flexible spending arrangements increases to $3,400, up $100 from the prior year.\n\n- **AMT Exemption:** The AMT exemption amount for 2026 is $90,100 for singles and $140,200 for married couples filing jointly.\n\n- **Estate Tax Exemption:** The OBBBA made the TCJA-era estate tax exemption permanent and raised it to $15 million per person beginning in 2026, adjusted for inflation moving forward.\n\n## Source Documents\n\n- The full text of Revenue Procedure 2025-32 is available directly from the IRS at: [irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-25-32.pdf](https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rp-25-32.pdf)\n- The IRS news release is at: [irs.gov newsroom](https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill)\n- The Tax Foundation's analysis is at: [taxfoundation.org](https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/)"],"durationSeconds":36.657108582999996}}
