{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014CECrVdA2d3aAaEuZCXdoj","type":"tool_result","content":"# 2026 Federal Income Tax Brackets\n\n**Publication Details:**\n- Published: January 1, 2026\n- Last Updated: March 11, 2026\n- Authors: Garrett Watson and Alex Durante\n\n## Key Information\n\nThe article indicates that \"the income limits for all tax brackets and all filers will be adjusted for inflation\" with approximately 2.7 percent increases overall. However, **the specific dollar thresholds for each filing status are not included in the provided excerpt**.\n\n## Available Data\n\nThe document confirms seven tax rates apply in 2026:\n- 10%, 12%, 22%, 24%, 32%, 35%, and 37%\n\nFor single filers and married couples filing jointly, the top 37% bracket begins at:\n- **Single:** $640,600+\n- **Married Filing Jointly:** $768,600+\n\n## Note\n\nThe content appears truncated (\"Content truncated due to length...\"), meaning the complete tax bracket tables for all five filing statuses—single, married filing jointly, married filing separately, head of household, and qualifying surviving spouse—are not visible in the provided webpage excerpt. You would need to access the full article directly to obtain all threshold amounts."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"a40fad0f-e384-4618-a234-df154e375256","tool_use_result":{"bytes":195154,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# 2026 Federal Income Tax Brackets\n\n**Publication Details:**\n- Published: January 1, 2026\n- Last Updated: March 11, 2026\n- Authors: Garrett Watson and Alex Durante\n\n## Key Information\n\nThe article indicates that \"the income limits for all tax brackets and all filers will be adjusted for inflation\" with approximately 2.7 percent increases overall. However, **the specific dollar thresholds for each filing status are not included in the provided excerpt**.\n\n## Available Data\n\nThe document confirms seven tax rates apply in 2026:\n- 10%, 12%, 22%, 24%, 32%, 35%, and 37%\n\nFor single filers and married couples filing jointly, the top 37% bracket begins at:\n- **Single:** $640,600+\n- **Married Filing Jointly:** $768,600+\n\n## Note\n\nThe content appears truncated (\"Content truncated due to length...\"), meaning the complete tax bracket tables for all five filing statuses—single, married filing jointly, married filing separately, head of household, and qualifying surviving spouse—are not visible in the provided webpage excerpt. You would need to access the full article directly to obtain all threshold amounts.","durationMs":4850,"url":"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BcHbfZxuMGpFAapJePLkYg","type":"tool_result","content":"# 2026 Federal Income Tax Brackets\n\n**Publication Details:**\n- Revenue Procedure 2025-32\n- Released: October 9, 2025 (IR-2025-103)\n\n**Available Bracket Information:**\n\nThe IRS announcement provides complete bracket data for **Single and Married Filing Jointly** filers only:\n\n**Single Taxpayers:**\n- 10% up to $12,400\n- 12% over $12,400 to $50,400\n- 22% over $50,400 to $105,700\n- 24% over $105,700 to $201,775\n- 32% over $201,775 to $256,225\n- 35% over $256,225 to $640,600\n- 37% over $640,600\n\n**Married Filing Jointly:**\n- 10% up to $24,800\n- 12% over $24,800 to $100,800\n- 22% over $100,800 to $211,400\n- 24% over $211,400 to $403,550\n- 32% over $403,550 to $512,450\n- 35% over $512,450 to $768,700\n- 37% over $768,700\n\n**Important Limitation:** The source document does not provide specific bracket thresholds for married filing separately, head of household, or qualifying surviving spouse filers for 2026. The announcement states that \"Revenue Procedure 2025-32 provides details,\" suggesting complete information exists in that PDF document."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"d59dac0d-27c6-43a4-9789-cde5703f7403","tool_use_result":{"bytes":102223,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# 2026 Federal Income Tax Brackets\n\n**Publication Details:**\n- Revenue Procedure 2025-32\n- Released: October 9, 2025 (IR-2025-103)\n\n**Available Bracket Information:**\n\nThe IRS announcement provides complete bracket data for **Single and Married Filing Jointly** filers only:\n\n**Single Taxpayers:**\n- 10% up to $12,400\n- 12% over $12,400 to $50,400\n- 22% over $50,400 to $105,700\n- 24% over $105,700 to $201,775\n- 32% over $201,775 to $256,225\n- 35% over $256,225 to $640,600\n- 37% over $640,600\n\n**Married Filing Jointly:**\n- 10% up to $24,800\n- 12% over $24,800 to $100,800\n- 22% over $100,800 to $211,400\n- 24% over $211,400 to $403,550\n- 32% over $403,550 to $512,450\n- 35% over $512,450 to $768,700\n- 37% over $768,700\n\n**Important Limitation:** The source document does not provide specific bracket thresholds for married filing separately, head of household, or qualifying surviving spouse filers for 2026. The announcement states that \"Revenue Procedure 2025-32 provides details,\" suggesting complete information exists in that PDF document.","durationMs":5134,"url":"https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XNJbHRyGnnzcxdTTGwqjk5","type":"tool_result","content":"# 2026 Federal Income Tax Brackets\n\nBased on the IRS website content provided, **the 2026 tax brackets are not included in this document**. The page explicitly states:\n\n> \"Find the 2026 tax rates (for money you earn in 2026)\"\n\nHowever, this is presented as a link to external information rather than the actual 2026 rates themselves.\n\n## What IS Available\n\nThe document provides **complete 2025 tax brackets** for all filing statuses:\n\n- **Single**\n- **Married Filing Jointly/Qualifying Surviving Spouse**\n- **Married Filing Separately**\n- **Head of Household**\n\n## How to Find 2026 Brackets\n\nAccording to the source, you should access the IRS newsroom announcement titled \"IRS releases tax inflation adjustments for tax year 2026, including amendments from the One, Big, Beautiful Bill\" to obtain the 2026 rates. The current document only covers 2025 tax year information."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"2911d222-c9e9-43f3-bd4d-08812e982cfa","tool_use_result":{"bytes":104971,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# 2026 Federal Income Tax Brackets\n\nBased on the IRS website content provided, **the 2026 tax brackets are not included in this document**. The page explicitly states:\n\n> \"Find the 2026 tax rates (for money you earn in 2026)\"\n\nHowever, this is presented as a link to external information rather than the actual 2026 rates themselves.\n\n## What IS Available\n\nThe document provides **complete 2025 tax brackets** for all filing statuses:\n\n- **Single**\n- **Married Filing Jointly/Qualifying Surviving Spouse**\n- **Married Filing Separately**\n- **Head of Household**\n\n## How to Find 2026 Brackets\n\nAccording to the source, you should access the IRS newsroom announcement titled \"IRS releases tax inflation adjustments for tax year 2026, including amendments from the One, Big, Beautiful Bill\" to obtain the 2026 rates. The current document only covers 2025 tax year information.","durationMs":5429,"url":"https://www.irs.gov/filing/federal-income-tax-rates-and-brackets"}}
