{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QiS5a4y7xJfXhw3Pf6SomC","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"2026 tax brackets head of household married filing separately qualifying surviving spouse exact amounts site:kiplinger.com OR site:taxfoundation.org\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"IRS releases tax inflation adjustments for tax year 2026, including amendments from the One, Big, Beautiful Bill | Internal Revenue Service\",\"url\":\"https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill\"},{\"title\":\"Standard Deduction 2025-2026: Amounts, How It Works - NerdWallet\",\"url\":\"https://www.nerdwallet.com/taxes/learn/standard-deduction\"},{\"title\":\"2025-2026 Tax Brackets & Federal Income Tax Rates | H&R Block®\",\"url\":\"https://www.hrblock.com/tax-center/irs/tax-brackets-and-rates/what-are-the-tax-brackets/\"},{\"title\":\"2026 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation\",\"url\":\"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/\"},{\"title\":\"Tax Brackets 2026 : Married vs. Single Filing Guide\",\"url\":\"https://swatadvisors.com/irs-tax-brackets-for-2026/\"},{\"title\":\"IRS Releases 2026 Cost-of-Living Adjustments, Includes Amendments…\",\"url\":\"https://www.doeren.com/viewpoint/irs-releases-2026-cost-of-living-adjustments-includes-amendments-from-obbba\"},{\"title\":\"The Updated Federal Income Tax Brackets for the 2026 Tax Year | Chase\",\"url\":\"https://www.chase.com/personal/investments/learning-and-insights/article/tax-brackets-2026\"},{\"title\":\"Filing Taxes as a Widow(er) in 2026: Complete Guide for Surviving Spouses\",\"url\":\"https://www.wingsforwidows.org/popular-articles/how-to-file-taxes-in-2026-as-a-recent-widow-or-widower\"},{\"title\":\"IRS Releases 2026 Tax Brackets, Contribution Limits, Other Tax Updates | PERA On The Issues\",\"url\":\"https://copera.org/pera-on-the-issues/irs-releases-2026-tax-brackets-contribution-limits-other-tax-updates\"},{\"title\":\"2026 individual tax brackets, and tips for understanding what you pay | Principal\",\"url\":\"https://www.principal.com/individuals/learn/individual-tax-brackets-understand-what-you-pay\"}]\n\nI found information about 2026 tax brackets and standard deductions. Here are the key details:\n\n## Standard Deductions for 2026\n\nFor tax year 2026, the standard deduction increases to $32,200 for married couples filing jointly. For single taxpayers and married individuals filing separately, the standard deduction rises to $16,100 for tax year 2026, and for heads of households, the standard deduction will be $24,150.\n\n## Qualifying Surviving Spouses\n\nQualifying surviving spouses are filers whose spouses have passed away within the past two years. Qualifying surviving spouses are taxed at married filing jointly rates, so they should reference that tax rate table. This means qualifying surviving spouses use the same standard deduction as married filing jointly: $32,200.\n\n## Tax Bracket Information\n\nIn 2026, the income limits for all tax brackets and all filers will be adjusted for inflation. The federal income tax has seven tax rates in 2026: 10 percent, 12 percent, 22 percent, 24 percent, 32 percent, 35 percent, and 37 percent.\n\nThe top marginal income tax rate of 37 percent will hit taxpayers with taxable income above $640,600 for single filers and above $768,600 for married couples filing jointly.\n\nFor the complete detailed tax bracket tables by filing status (Head of Household, Married Filing Separately, and Qualifying Surviving Spouse), you can consult the IRS official source or the Tax Foundation website linked in the search results, as they provide the full breakdown of all seven tax brackets with exact income thresholds for each filing status.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"9ca1b80a-38d0-41ef-a84b-7ed5ea632e05","tool_use_result":{"query":"2026 tax brackets head of household married filing separately qualifying surviving spouse exact amounts site:kiplinger.com OR site:taxfoundation.org","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_019RynwrLLA2jTwRvv4hNHcT","content":[{"title":"IRS releases tax inflation adjustments for tax year 2026, including amendments from the One, Big, Beautiful Bill | Internal Revenue Service","url":"https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-releases-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026-including-amendments-from-the-one-big-beautiful-bill"},{"title":"Standard Deduction 2025-2026: Amounts, How It Works - NerdWallet","url":"https://www.nerdwallet.com/taxes/learn/standard-deduction"},{"title":"2025-2026 Tax Brackets & Federal Income Tax Rates | H&R Block®","url":"https://www.hrblock.com/tax-center/irs/tax-brackets-and-rates/what-are-the-tax-brackets/"},{"title":"2026 Tax Brackets and Federal Income Tax Rates | Tax Foundation","url":"https://taxfoundation.org/data/all/federal/2026-tax-brackets/"},{"title":"Tax Brackets 2026 : Married vs. Single Filing Guide","url":"https://swatadvisors.com/irs-tax-brackets-for-2026/"},{"title":"IRS Releases 2026 Cost-of-Living Adjustments, Includes Amendments…","url":"https://www.doeren.com/viewpoint/irs-releases-2026-cost-of-living-adjustments-includes-amendments-from-obbba"},{"title":"The Updated Federal Income Tax Brackets for the 2026 Tax Year | Chase","url":"https://www.chase.com/personal/investments/learning-and-insights/article/tax-brackets-2026"},{"title":"Filing Taxes as a Widow(er) in 2026: Complete Guide for Surviving Spouses","url":"https://www.wingsforwidows.org/popular-articles/how-to-file-taxes-in-2026-as-a-recent-widow-or-widower"},{"title":"IRS Releases 2026 Tax Brackets, Contribution Limits, Other Tax Updates | PERA On The Issues","url":"https://copera.org/pera-on-the-issues/irs-releases-2026-tax-brackets-contribution-limits-other-tax-updates"},{"title":"2026 individual tax brackets, and tips for understanding what you pay | Principal","url":"https://www.principal.com/individuals/learn/individual-tax-brackets-understand-what-you-pay"}]},"I found information about 2026 tax brackets and standard deductions. Here are the key details:\n\n## Standard Deductions for 2026\n\nFor tax year 2026, the standard deduction increases to $32,200 for married couples filing jointly. For single taxpayers and married individuals filing separately, the standard deduction rises to $16,100 for tax year 2026, and for heads of households, the standard deduction will be $24,150.\n\n## Qualifying Surviving Spouses\n\nQualifying surviving spouses are filers whose spouses have passed away within the past two years. Qualifying surviving spouses are taxed at married filing jointly rates, so they should reference that tax rate table. This means qualifying surviving spouses use the same standard deduction as married filing jointly: $32,200.\n\n## Tax Bracket Information\n\nIn 2026, the income limits for all tax brackets and all filers will be adjusted for inflation. The federal income tax has seven tax rates in 2026: 10 percent, 12 percent, 22 percent, 24 percent, 32 percent, 35 percent, and 37 percent.\n\nThe top marginal income tax rate of 37 percent will hit taxpayers with taxable income above $640,600 for single filers and above $768,600 for married couples filing jointly.\n\nFor the complete detailed tax bracket tables by filing status (Head of Household, Married Filing Separately, and Qualifying Surviving Spouse), you can consult the IRS official source or the Tax Foundation website linked in the search results, as they provide the full breakdown of all seven tax brackets with exact income thresholds for each filing status."],"durationSeconds":7.60809825000001}}
