{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01AAWhkCvLq2XAhEbXf6XGeb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the complete data. Let me also fetch the H&R Block page and one more corroborating source to verify the numbers. Let me also check: the search said qualifying surviving spouse uses the same brackets as married filing jointly.\n\nLet me verify by checking a couple more sources for the qualifying surviving spouse brackets.\n\nAlso, I notice the Head of Household brackets have:\n- 32%: $201,776 to $256,200\n- But single has 32%: $201,776 to $256,225\n\nThat's slightly different ($256,200 vs $256,225). Let me check the current_value.json:\n- HoH 32% max: $256,200 ✓\n\n\n- Single 32% max: $256,225 ✓\n\nWait, I'm seeing a discrepancy in the 24% bracket threshold. The current data shows $201,750 as the max for HoH's 24% bracket, but the search results indicate $201,775. That's a $25 difference I need to reconcile. I'm noticing the discrepancy between the search results showing $201,775 for HoH's 24% bracket and the current_value.json showing $201,750—there's a $25 difference that needs resolving. Looking at historical patterns, HoH and single brackets typically align, so I should verify which figure is correct by checking the actual IRS data for 2025 rather than relying on potentially outdated information. I'm noticing a discrepancy between the current data and search results—the HoH bracket shows $201,750 in one source but $201,775 in another, which matches the single filer rate. Since these brackets historically align, the $25 difference might be an error in the current file, so I need to verify against the official IRS data. is $201,775 to $256,225. The difference at both ends is $25. That's suspicious. It could be that HoH genuinely has slightly different boundaries or it could be a rounding issue.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully - in the IRC, the head of household bracket thresholds ARE different from single for some brackets but NOT for others. For 2025:\n- Single 10%: up to $11,600 / HoH 10%: up to $16,550\n- Single 12%: up to $47,150 / HoH 12%: up to $63,100\n- Single 22%: up to $100,525 / HoH 22%: up to $100,500 (different!)\n- Single 24%: up to $191,950 / HoH 24%: up to $191,950 (same!)\n- Single 32%: up to $243,725 / HoH 32%: up to $243,700 (different by $25!)\n- Single 35%: up to $609,350 / HoH 35%: up to $609,350 (same!)\n\nSo the pattern from 2025 shows HoH sometimes has $25 differences in specific brackets. Looking at 2026, I'm seeing the same $25 discrepancy at the 32% boundary, which suggests this might be consistent with how the IRS sets these thresholds rather than a rounding error. The question becomes whether HoH's 24% and 32% boundaries in 2026 follow the same $25 offset pattern we saw in 2025. The search results consistently show $201,775 as the upper limit for the 24% bracket for head of household filers in 2026, which aligns with the single filer amount, though the current_value.json file lists $201,750. I'm going to look for additional confirmation from other sources like NerdWallet or H&R Block to resolve this discrepancy.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2709,"cache_read_input_tokens":37777,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2709,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"db3d3a72-4e11-44dd-bf48-87635630a074"}
