{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CqXu2WPLWPqNvXQVsgNjEn","type":"tool_result","content":"# 2026 Federal Income Tax Brackets\n\nBased on the Chase article, complete bracket information for all filing statuses is presented in a chart, but the document only provides detailed bracket examples for **single filers**:\n\n## Single Filers (Detailed in Article):\n- 10% on $0 to $12,400\n- 12% on $12,401 to $50,400\n- 22% on $50,401 to $105,700\n- [Remaining brackets 4-7 referenced but not specified in text]\n\n## Other Filing Statuses:\nThe article states: \"Below we outline the updated brackets\" and references \"The chart displays the 2026 U.S. federal income tax brackets for four filing statuses: head of household, single, married filing separately and married filing jointly.\"\n\nHowever, **the actual numerical brackets for married filing jointly, married filing separately, head of household, and qualifying surviving spouse are not provided in the text content**. The document indicates a chart exists with this information, but the specific dollar thresholds are not transcribed in the webpage text provided.\n\n**Recommendation:** Consult the IRS Revenue Procedure 2025-32 (cited as the source) or the visual chart on Chase's website directly for complete bracket data across all five filing statuses."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"727a57fa-3eda-4fc0-a7db-40f86341640d","tool_use_result":{"bytes":585789,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# 2026 Federal Income Tax Brackets\n\nBased on the Chase article, complete bracket information for all filing statuses is presented in a chart, but the document only provides detailed bracket examples for **single filers**:\n\n## Single Filers (Detailed in Article):\n- 10% on $0 to $12,400\n- 12% on $12,401 to $50,400\n- 22% on $50,401 to $105,700\n- [Remaining brackets 4-7 referenced but not specified in text]\n\n## Other Filing Statuses:\nThe article states: \"Below we outline the updated brackets\" and references \"The chart displays the 2026 U.S. federal income tax brackets for four filing statuses: head of household, single, married filing separately and married filing jointly.\"\n\nHowever, **the actual numerical brackets for married filing jointly, married filing separately, head of household, and qualifying surviving spouse are not provided in the text content**. The document indicates a chart exists with this information, but the specific dollar thresholds are not transcribed in the webpage text provided.\n\n**Recommendation:** Consult the IRS Revenue Procedure 2025-32 (cited as the source) or the visual chart on Chase's website directly for complete bracket data across all five filing statuses.","durationMs":4843,"url":"https://www.chase.com/personal/investments/learning-and-insights/article/tax-brackets-2026"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QY9NtsoxfUUYxYGbmkuktV","type":"tool_result","content":"# 2026 Federal Income Tax Brackets\n\nBased on the document provided, I can confirm the standard deduction amounts and general bracket structure, but **the webpage does not display the complete tax bracket tables with exact dollar thresholds for all filing statuses.**\n\n## What the Document Confirms:\n\n**Standard Deductions (2026):**\n- Single: $16,100\n- Married Filing Jointly: $32,200\n- Married Filing Separately: $16,100\n- Head of Household: $23,950\n\n**Bracket Structure:**\nThe document states that \"The seven-bracket structure (10%-37%) remains\" with thresholds increased \"about 2%-3% from 2025.\"\n\n**Specific Thresholds Mentioned:**\n- Single filers: 37% rate begins at $609,350\n- Married Filing Jointly: 37% rate begins at $731,100\n- The 22% bracket for married couples now extends above $200,000\n- The 24% band extends close to $384,000\n\n## Critical Limitation:\n\nThe document references data tables showing complete brackets for each filing status, but **the actual numerical thresholds for all bracket boundaries are embedded in images that cannot be extracted as text from this HTML source**. The webpage notes it contains \"Data table\" images but these pixel-based files don't provide extractable data.\n\nFor precise threshold information across all brackets and filing statuses, you'd need to reference the source cited: IRS Rev. Proc. 2025-32."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"577029ba-c4ba-4ae0-983d-0cf11d24705d","tool_use_result":{"bytes":70318,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# 2026 Federal Income Tax Brackets\n\nBased on the document provided, I can confirm the standard deduction amounts and general bracket structure, but **the webpage does not display the complete tax bracket tables with exact dollar thresholds for all filing statuses.**\n\n## What the Document Confirms:\n\n**Standard Deductions (2026):**\n- Single: $16,100\n- Married Filing Jointly: $32,200\n- Married Filing Separately: $16,100\n- Head of Household: $23,950\n\n**Bracket Structure:**\nThe document states that \"The seven-bracket structure (10%-37%) remains\" with thresholds increased \"about 2%-3% from 2025.\"\n\n**Specific Thresholds Mentioned:**\n- Single filers: 37% rate begins at $609,350\n- Married Filing Jointly: 37% rate begins at $731,100\n- The 22% bracket for married couples now extends above $200,000\n- The 24% band extends close to $384,000\n\n## Critical Limitation:\n\nThe document references data tables showing complete brackets for each filing status, but **the actual numerical thresholds for all bracket boundaries are embedded in images that cannot be extracted as text from this HTML source**. The webpage notes it contains \"Data table\" images but these pixel-based files don't provide extractable data.\n\nFor precise threshold information across all brackets and filing statuses, you'd need to reference the source cited: IRS Rev. Proc. 2025-32.","durationMs":6574,"url":"https://millancpa.com/insights/2026-irs-tax-brackets-standard-deductions-capital-gains-amt"}}
