{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01QHdyQQgxsDtDWUR65bg8TX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Hmm, the millancpa page mentions different numbers: single 37% at $609,350 and MFJ 37% at $731,100. These sound like DIFFERENT brackets - perhaps those are the pre-OBBBA numbers? Let me check. \n\nActually, the TCJA was set to expire at the end of 2025. The One Big Beautiful Bill Act (OBBBA) made the TCJA rates permanent. So for 2026, with the OBBBA, the rates stay at 10/12/22/24/32/35/37%. Without the OBBBA, the rates would have reverted to the pre-TCJA rates which were different.\n \nRight, I'm looking at the bracket thresholds themselves, not just the rates. The OBBBA locked in the TCJA bracket structure for 2026, but without it, we'd be back to the pre-TCJA brackets. Comparing the 2025 thresholds (single 37% at $626,350, MFJ at $751,600) to what the 2026 brackets would be with OBBBA (single 37% at $640,600, MFJ at $768,000), those millancpa numbers look like they might be showing the old pre-TCJA structure that would've kicked in without the OBBBA.\n\nSince the pre-TCJA top rate was 39.6% and not 37%, those millancpa figures don't align with either scenario, so I'm setting that source aside. Let me work from the IRS newsroom data I've confirmed, which should give me the authoritative 2025 brackets to build from. I'm cross-checking the tax bracket thresholds against the search results—there's a discrepancy in the Head of Household brackets where the 24% threshold should be $201,775 rather than what's currently stored, and I need to verify where the 32% bracket actually caps out. Looking at the 2025 tax bracket data from Revenue Procedure 2024-40, I see that both Single and Head of Household filers have the same $191,950 threshold for the 24% bracket, though there's a slight discrepancy in the lower bound ($100,525 for Single vs $100,500 for HoH). Now I need to verify these precise figures against what's in the current JSON file to identify where the inconsistencies are. The 5.1% increase is higher than typical inflation adjustments, which suggests the 2026 brackets might have been recalculated differently after the TCJA was made permanent under Section 70101 of the OBBBA. I'm confident the HoH 24% bracket threshold is $201,775 based on consistent search results, even though the JSON file shows $201,750. Let me check a couple more sources like the Morgan Stanley and COPERA documents to nail down the HoH brackets definitively.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1023,"cache_read_input_tokens":43768,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1023,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"546702c8-81bb-4fa7-8850-479bfe1a978d"}
