{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_016uYsYrcMbodoNRHLFTSJwF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The swatadvisors source shows DIFFERENT numbers for several brackets. In particular:\n- HoH 24%: $105,701 to $201,750 (not $201,775)\n- HoH 32%: $201,751 to $250,500 (not $256,200)\n- HoH 35%: $250,501 to $626,350 (not $640,600)\n- HoH 37%: Over $626,350 (not $640,600)\n- MFJ 35%: $512,451 to $626,350 (not $768,700)\n\n\n- MFJ 37%: Over $626,350\n\nThese numbers look like pre-TCJA brackets, which suggests the swatadvisors page might be confusing the rate structure—the OBBBA made the TCJA permanent, so 2026 brackets should follow the TCJA rates with inflation adjustments, not revert to the older 10%, 15%, 25%, 28%, 33%, 35%, 39.6% structure.\n\nSwatadvisors isn't a reliable source anyway—it's not even on the approved host list (IRS, Tax Foundation, Tax Policy Center, Kiplinger). I should focus on the IRS newsroom data and the consistent search results I've found for the Single filer brackets.\n\nNow I'm compiling the complete 2024 tax bracket data for both Single and Married Filing Jointly filers...\n\nGenerating tax bracket table... Looking at the IRC Section 1(j)(2)(A) language, I can see the 24% bracket for Heads of Household starts over $162,718 and ends at $207,350 in the 2017 base amounts. For 2026, these get adjusted by the cost-of-living factor and rounded to the nearest $25, but I need to verify what that adjustment actually produces. Let me check the 2025 brackets from the IRS guidance to work backwards and confirm the pattern.\n\nNow I'm reviewing the actual 2025 tax bracket thresholds for both filing statuses to see where the boundaries fall and whether there's been any shift in how the brackets align between single filers and heads of household. Looking at the 32%/35% boundary, the pattern holds consistently across both years with that $25 difference between HoH and Single filers. For the 24%/32% boundary, I'm calculating the inflation adjustment ratios to see whether both filing statuses increased by the same percentage or if there's a $25 rounding difference like the upper bracket. The base amounts under IRC Section 1(j)(2) suggest the HoH bracket might be slightly lower, but I need to verify the exact 2017 base figure to confirm. I'm hitting a wall with the PDF parsing, so let me try searching for the Tax Foundation's breakdown instead—they should have all five filing status schedules laid out clearly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2899,"cache_read_input_tokens":44791,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2899,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":12,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ec58da6-4ff1-4815-8056-168ff90521c1","uuid":"39a3fdfc-1536-4e1c-9d1c-8d2e6a7d07f9"}
